  "texts": [
    "In the improper context, representation-independent hardness means that learning remains hard regardless of the form the algorithm represents its hypothesis, on the basis that the hypothesis can evaluated in polynomial time.",
    "This means that if NP = co-NP, then it follows that PH = NP.",
    "It is widely believed that a collapse of the PH is implausible.",
    "Recent work in algorithmic fairness indicates that there are inevitable trade-offs between, on the one hand, different concepts of fairness, and on the other, between fairness and accuracy (Berk et al. 2021).134 See, e.g.",
    "Wellner (2021) for the topic of gender biases, and Liang et al. (2022) for a \"holistic\" evaluation of LLMs using multiple metrics and test cases."
